This morning the world lost a great one, Jimmy Shaffer. A great man, husband, friend. I met Jimmy in early 2003 and we became fast friends. We worked together almost fifteen of the last twenty years. Even though I didn’t grow up with Jimmy as a kid, I can’t recall what life is like without his friendship. Our daily interactions of texts, memes and trading random Sopranos lines were simply hilarious. 

Jimmy was one of the most generous people I’ve ever known. He gave relentlessly without ever expecting anything in return. He gave because he loved people, and making people happy, especially his wife Marie Joy, his close family and friends, his customers and his Aikido community.  Jimmy was fiercely loyal. He took work and relationships seriously, but had a hellacious sense of humor. 

Jimmy was one of one. Losing loved ones is hard… but this one hurts different. Please keep his wife and family in your prayers. 

Rest in peace my dear friend!

The final trip of the year was a quick busy few days in Miami. Thanks to my friends at @cigarsnobmag for lunch, and the invitation to join your podcast! I was really nice to catch up on @feriotego and do a little bourbon tasting at the same time! Win win!!

Today was quite a tribute to my friend Jimmy Shaffer.  Standing room only services and endless stories of Jimmy’s love and generosity.  Having a nearly twenty year friendship, and working together almost fifteen of those…. plus the daily texts, calls and messages… it’s easy to think that our relationship was just a touch “extra”… just “a little closer”. But, what has been extraordinary to realize is EVERYONE who loved Jimmy felt the same way as I. Jimmy made everyone feel like his Number One. 

And so how does a 45 year old guy get called back to the Lord when he’s doing so much for so many here?  Because Heaven needed him more. I’m not sure what God needed done up there, but it must have been a serious piece of work… because they just recruited the greatest angel on earth in a hurry. 

Heaven needed Jimmy more.

Handmade premium cigars use “long filler” leaves that run the length of the cigar itself. About two thirds of the stem/center vein is removed from each leaf, starting from the stalk side towards the tip, prior to being used in a blend. The remaining portion of the stem serves an important role in the function of those leaves within the “bunch” of handmade premium cigars, particularly around the draw, as they act as a fulcrum to fold each leaf around, and they preserve channels within the bunch through which air (and smoke) can pass delivering flavor to the palate. 

HOWEVER, sometimes stems can overlap or intersect and cause problems with draw- and those problems occasionally evade hand inspection, weighing and other quality control measures including even the draw master machine. 

But ALL premium cigars have stems, because they’re all long-filler.  I picked some of my favorites to cut, draw through and light to demonstrate how well they were made and performed, and then dissected each one to show the consistent presence of stems within their flawless construction. 

All handmade premium cigars have stems- and they rarely cause a problem. But obviously, a bad draw is frustrating, especially when you consider all the great lengths manufacturers go through to mitigate problems and preserve and maintain quality one handmade premium cigar at a time. Sometimes if a tight draw occurs, you can try rolling the cigar gently on a flat surface to shift the fillers. Others may use a “poker” to try and create new channels of air while others may try and remove a stem from the bunch to open the draw. 

Premium cigars aren’t perfect… but rather perfectly imperfect. They are each “one of one”, made one at a time, from scratch, by hand… over and over to bring joy and pleasure. And they all have stems. 

Thanks to @cigardojo  for inspiring this conversation.

An artist’s pursuit is never “perfection”… because artists know that no such thing exists. But rather an artist’s pursuit is one of commitment to improvement and development in their craft. 

A new album, or book, or painting is just part of the evolution of the artist… and the record of their work serves as an archive and a record that continues to provide joy. 

Blending is quite similar, but in our case we preserve the historical work in real time with core blends. Enjoying a Metropolitan or Timeless is experiencing a moment in time, recreated today. Just as your favorite band performs their biggest hits along with new songs in a concert, so too do we continue to preserve and maintain our hits while still pursuing artistic development in new work. 

I’m grateful for those who enjoy our work… and am SO grateful when you share your enthusiasm with others. The work continues.

The Ferio Tego Elegancia and Generoso are completely different experiences, much like Chardonnay and Cabernet Sauvignon. However, as is also the case with these two wines- a winemaker lends a certain “style” to the wines that perhaps offers a point of similarity. So too is the case with these blends. Despite how radically different the flavors are they share a wonderfully creamy body and mouth feel. 

The “The 2022 Elegancia is extraordinarily complex.  The flavors are graceful and refreshing, yet still rich and present.  A mouth-filling, full-bodied smoke with a creamy finish and a wonderfully engaging development of flavors that evolves dramatically with each puff.” -MH @michaelherklots 

“The 2022 Generoso is an intense savory smoke that delivers a wide range of rich, dark flavors, in a full yet smooth body. It’s wonderfully balanced and incredibly engaging as the flavors develop throughout the experience.” -MH

I often consider character first when blending, and then work to polish and tweak flavor.

I am fatigued by the “experts” in my feed these days.  I have an endless delivery of “what I just learned” and “here’s what you need to know right now.”

Please stop.

Stop “learning to show” and get back to “learning to grow” in your discipline.

I’m grateful to have spent a great deal of time with experts in their respective fields - chefs, winemakers, blenders, doctors, entrepreneurs…  And if you were to ask them if they considered themselves an expert, they would answer unequivocally, “no”.

The greatest experts I know would all consider themselves perpetual students of their crafts.

I don’t know a single chef that isn’t refining recipes and techniques, a winemaker who isn’t exploring practices in the vineyard and in the winery, a musician who isn’t practicing to better master their instrument… a doctor who isn’t studying updated medical practices… knowing that the process is a never-ending pursuit to be better.

Real expertise isn’t a self-proclaimed badge; it’s not earned by watching a few videos or attending a couple of classes. It’s an evolving journey, a commitment to constant learning, applying it, and learning from it.  Repeat. Repeat. Repeat

Beware of the self-proclaimed expert.  I’ve found that in general, those who claim to be experts in their field…. Are not. 

Expertise isn’t a destination.  It’s a process.  Surround yourself with perpetual students who have been learning longer than you have and in different areas than you and apply that to your own process.

My first day of the New Year I always pick up pending projects. Young projects change quite a bit in the early aging process.
